[1] Netherlands: NOT
[2] Belgium: bovine, 1st case 2008

*****
[1] Netherlands: NOT
Date: Wed 30 Jul 2008
Source: Agrarisch Dagblad [in Dutch, trans. Mod.AS, edited]
<http://www.agd.nl/1057645/Nieuws/Artikel/VWA-nog-geen-blauwtong-in-Nederland.htm>


VWA: no bluetongue yet in the Netherlands
-----------------------------------------
According to the Dutch Food and Consumer Product Safety Authority
(VWA), no new outbreaks have, so far, been recorded in the
Netherlands.

"Since April [2008] we have had more than 200 clinically suspected
cases, but not in even a single one has the virus been demonstrated,"
said the VWA spokesman.

New infections have already been recorded in neighboring Belgium and
Germany. The VWA is expecting such infections to occur during the
current year [2008], "but this will clearly be to a lesser extent,
thanks to the vaccination as well as to the fact that many animals
have already gone through infection last year [2007, and have,
subsequently, become immune. - Mod.AS]

Arjan den Hartog of the Royal Dutch Society of Veterinary Medicine
(KNMvD) says that the absence of new infections in the Netherlands is
rather remarkable. "The reason for that is not clear. The rate of
vaccination may have played its role to some extent, but this cannot
yet be said with certainty, since the infection pressure is not yet
very high."

The KNMvD notes that the absence of infection is not related to the
midges. "The midges are already fully active," says Den Hartog. It is
also not related to the rate of farmers' alertness. "Due to
vaccination, the alertness of farmers has rather increased, since
they carefully watch their animals to detect any post-vaccination
side effects."

[Byline: Mariska Vermaas]

--
